<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09030d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09030d">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09030d"> 30(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ Solomon&apos;s Throne</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;Le groupe <font color="green">[de monts]</font> le plus fameux, continue l&apos;auteur de la Nouvelle G&eacute;ographie universelle, est celui auquel on donne sp&eacute;cialement le nom de Thr&ocirc;ne de Salomon, Takht-i-Soula&iuml;man&hellip; Le sommet du nord, qui est aussi le plus haut (3444 m&egrave;tres), est une de ces nombreuses cimes sur lesquelles se serait arr&ecirc;t&eacute;e l&apos;arche de No&eacute;; une niche pratiqu&eacute;e dans le rocher, pr&egrave;s d&apos;un groupe de pierres consid&eacute;r&eacute; domme un temple, est le tr&ocirc;ne o&ugrave; s&apos;asseyait Salomon pour contempler l&apos;immense ab&icirc;me du monde. <br><font color="green">[&ldquo;The most famous group [of mountains]</font>, continues the author of the New Universal Geography, is that which is called specifically Solomon&apos;s Throne, Takht-i-Soula#<font color="green">[C3]</font>#<font color="green">[AF]</font>man &hellip; The northern summit, which is also the highest (3,444 metres), is one of those numerous peaks upon which Noah&apos;s Ark is supposed to have halted. A recess made within the rock, near a group of stones considered to be a temple, is the throne where Solomon withdrew to contemplate the immense abyss of the world.] <small> L&eacute;on Metchnikoff, <a name="LMCG" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LMCG"><cite title="source">La Civilisation et les grands fleuves Historiques</cite></a> (1889) 164</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
